  \begin {tikzcd}
    & \operatorname {im} \text {d}_{n+1}\ar [rr, hookrightarrow]\ar [dr, hookrightarrow]
    && \operatorname {ker} \text {d}_n\ar [dl, hookrightarrow] \\
    x_{n + 1}\ar [rr, "\text {d}_{n+1}"]\ar [ur, two heads] && x_n\ar [rr, "\text {d}_n"]\ar [dl, two heads]\ar [dr, two
    heads] && x_{n - 1}\makebox [0pt][l]{.} \\
    & \operatorname {coker} \text {d}_{n+1}\ar [rr, two heads] && \operatorname {im}
    \text {d}_n\ar [ur, hookrightarrow]
  \end {tikzcd}


 Indeed, since x_{n + 1}\twoheadrightarrow \operatorname {im} \text {d}_{n + 1}\to  x_{n - 1} is zero and the first
map is an epi, we have that \operatorname {im} \text {d}_{n + 1}\to  x_{n - 1} is zero, so it factors
through \ker  \text {d}_n, and similarly on the other side. The nth chain
homology H_n(x) of the complex is any of the following isomorphic objects of
A:
H_n(x) = \operatorname {coker}(\operatorname {im} \text {d}_{n + 1}\to  \ker  \text {d}_n) = \ker  (\operatorname {coker} \text {d}_{n + 1}\to  \operatorname {im} \text {d}_n) = \operatorname {im}(\ker  \text {d}_i\to \operatorname {coker} \text {d}_{i + 1}).

In particular, there is a natural map \operatorname {coim}{f}\to \operatorname {im}{f} making
the square





